==Distribution and habitat==
The purple sandpiper's breeding range extends from the arctic islands of northern Canada, eastwards to Greenland, Iceland, [[Svalbard]] and northern Scandinavia across to [[Western Siberia]] and the [[Taymyr Peninsula]]. In the high arctic the sandpiper breeds at low altitude on the tundra, sometimes far from the coastline, but in the subarctic regions of Sweden and Norway it breeds on barren mountain sides near the limit of the frozen ground. Birds breeding at high latitudes migrate south and spend the winter on rocky shores on both sides of the north Atlantic. They winter along the North America coast as far south as South Carolina and on the eastern Atlantic coast as far south as France and northern Iberia.<ref name=bow>{{cite journal | last1=Payne | first1=L.X. | last2=Pierce | first2=E.P. | date=2020 | title=Purple Sandpiper (''Calidris maritima''), version 1.0 | editor-last=Billerman | editor-first=S.M. | journal=Birds of the World | location=Ithaca, NY, USA | publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology | doi=10.2173/bow.pursan.01 }}</ref>

Birds wintering in northern Scotland and southwest Ireland migrate to Canada ([[Baffin Island]] and [[Devon Island]]) to breed.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=Summers | first1=R.W. | last2=Boland | first2=H. | last3=Colhoun | first3=K. | last4=Elkins | first4=N. | last5=Etheridge | first5=B. | last6=Foster | first6=S. | last7=Fox | first7=J.W. | last8=Mackie | first8=K. | last9=Quinn | first9=L.R. | last10=Swann | first10=R.L. | date=2014 | title=Contrasting trans-Atlantic migratory routes of Nearctic Purple Sandpipers ''Calidris maritima'' associated with low pressure systems in spring and winter | journal=Ardea | volume=102 | issue=2 | pages=139–152 | doi=10.5253/arde.v102i2.a4 | doi-access=free }}</ref>

In Britain, these birds occur in winter in good numbers principally along the east and south coasts, where they favour rocky shorelines adjacent to the sea.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} It is much rarer as a breeding bird, found only in a localised area of the [[Cairngorms National Park]], where 1–3 pairs have bred since 1978. Records of breeding by this species in the UK are monitored and archived by the [[Rare Breeding Birds Panel]].<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Sharrock | first=J.T.R. | author2=Rare Birds Breeding Panel | date=1980 | title=Rare breeding birds in the United Kingdom in 1978 | journal=British Birds | volume=73 | issue=1 | pages=5–26 [18] | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51097136}}</ref><ref>{{ cite journal | last=Holling | first=Mark | author2=Rare Birds Breeding Panel | date=2016 | title=Rare breeding birds in the United Kingdom in 2014 | journal=British Birds | volume=109 | issue=9 | pages=491–545 [521] }}</ref>

They are late [[bird migration|migrants]] and move to rocky, ice-free [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] coasts in winter.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Most go no further south than [[North Carolina]] and northern [[Portugal]]. They are fairly gregarious, forming small flocks, often with [[ruddy turnstone]]s. This species is tame and approachable.{{sfn|Cramp|1983|p=350}}<!-- cite only for last sentence-->

==Behaviour and ecology==
===Breeding===
[[File:Calidris maritima maritima MHNT.ZOO.2010.11.119.17.jpg|thumb|Eggs of ''C. maritima'']]
Their breeding habitat is the northern [[tundra]] on [[Arctic]] islands in [[Canada]] and coastal areas in [[Greenland]] and northwestern [[Europe]]. They can breed at one year of age. The male makes several scrapes on the ground; the female chooses one and lays 3 or 4 eggs. These are olive with brown blotches and are approximately {{cvt|37|x|26|mm}} in size. The male takes the major responsibility for incubation of the eggs which hatch in 21–22 days.{{sfn|Cramp|1983|p=353}} The chicks are covered with dense down. The upperparts have black and cinnamon patches with white specks; the underparts are mainly white.{{sfn|Cramp|1983|p=354}} Usually only the male tends the chicks which can feed themselves.{{sfn|Cramp|1983|p=353}} The maximum age recorded from [[Bird ringing|ring-recovery]] data in Europe is 20 years and 9 months for a bird recovered in Sweden.<ref name=euring>{{cite web |title=European Longevity Records |url=https://euring.org/data-and-codes/longevity-list?page=2 |publisher=Euring |access-date=13 November 2021 }}</ref>

An apparent case of [[Hybrid (biology)|hybridisation]] between this species and the [[dunlin]] has been reported from [[England]].<ref name=Millington1994/>

===Feeding===
These birds forage on rocky coasts, picking up food by sight.{{sfn|Cramp|1983|p=348}} They mainly eat arthropods and molluscs, mainly [[Littorinidae|littorinid]]s and [[mussel]]s, also some plant material. One of the main staples are [[seaweed fly|seaweed flies]] of the ''Coelopa'' genera (''[[Coelopa frigida|C. frigida]]'').<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Summers |first1=R. W. |last2=Smith |first2=S. |last3=Nicoll |first3=M. |last4=Atkinson |first4=N. K. |date=1990 |title=Tidal and sexual differences in the diet of Purple Sandpipers Calidris maritima in Scotland |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/00063659009477056 |journal=Bird Study |language=en |volume=37 |issue=3 |pages=187–194 |doi=10.1080/00063659009477056 |bibcode=1990BirdS..37..187S |issn=0006-3657}}</ref>

==Status==
The purple sandpiper has a large range – {{Convert|13600000|km2|sqmi}} – and although the population appears to be decreasing, the population is large (136,000-191,000 mature individuals as of 2024). The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) has judged that the threat to the species is of "[[Least-concern species|Least concern]]".<ref name="iucn status"/> The purple sandpiper is one of the species to which the ''[[Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds]]'' (AEWA) applies.<ref>{{ cite web | title=Species| url=https://www.unep-aewa.org/en/species | publisher=Agreement on the Conservation of African-Eurasian Migratory Waterbirds (AEWA) | access-date=14 November 2021}}</ref>


